        <div type="footnotes">
            <note xml:id="foot.f1">CD had previously asked Treat for information on the size of insects caught by <hi rend="italic">Dionaea</hi> (Venus fly trap), suspecting that small insects were able to escape (<ref target="../bibliographies/bibl_1581.xml" resp="#mjhawkins"><hi rend="italic">Correspondence</hi></ref> vol. 21, <ref target="./DCP-LETT-8719.xml" resp="#mjhawkins">letter to Mary Treat, 1 January 1873</ref>); he argued in <ref target="../bibliographies/bibl_4097.xml" resp="#mjhawkins"><hi rend="italic">Insectivorous plants</hi></ref>, pp. 311–12, that it was advantageous to the plants to trap only larger insects.</note>
            <note xml:id="foot.f2">CD used this observation by Treat as evidence that strong insects could occasionally escape from <hi rend="italic">Dionaea</hi> (<ref target="../bibliographies/bibl_4097.xml" resp="#mjhawkins"><hi rend="italic">Insectivorous plants</hi></ref>, p. 312).</note>
            <note xml:id="foot.f3"><hi rend="italic">Metapodius nasulus</hi> is a synonym of <hi rend="italic">Acanthocephala femorata</hi>, the Florida leaf-footed bug; <hi rend="italic">Cimex tristis</hi>, the squash bug, is now <hi rend="italic">Anasa tristis</hi>. Both are in the family Coreidae.</note>
            <note xml:id="foot.f4">CD cited this observation by Treat in <ref target="../bibliographies/bibl_4097.xml" resp="#mjhawkins"><hi rend="italic">Insectivorous plants</hi></ref>, p. 313 n.</note>
            <note xml:id="foot.f5">For CD’s most recent correspondence with Treat on <hi rend="italic">Drosera</hi> (sundew), see <ref target="../bibliographies/bibl_1581.xml" resp="#mjhawkins"><hi rend="italic">Correspondence</hi></ref> vol. 21, <ref target="./DCP-LETT-8989.xml" resp="#mjhawkins">letter from Mary Treat, 28 July 1873</ref>, and <ref target="./DCP-LETT-9005B.xml" resp="#mjhawkins">letter to Mary Treat, 12 August 1873</ref>.</note>
            <note xml:id="foot.f6">Treat refers to <ref target="../nameregs/nameregs_7403.xml" resp="#mjhawkins">Thomas Fanning Wood</ref> of Wilmington, North Carolina; <hi rend="italic">Dionaea</hi> is native to a few areas in North and South Carolina only.</note>
        </div>        
            
